From 6ed4ce4fca298b18917c2d56aa4cc1c81530d64f Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Johannes Schindelin <johannes.schindelin@gmx.de>
Date: Mon, 11 May 2026 17:52:56 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 22/25] execute_cmd: remove dead REDIRECT_BOTH bail-out from
 fast path

The fast-pipeline commit added `if (pipe_out == REDIRECT_BOTH) return
FAST_SPAWN_DECLINE' under the impression that `cmd |& cmd2' would
reach fast_spawn_command with REDIRECT_BOTH as pipe_out.  It does not.
The parser at parse.y:1473-1481 rewrites `cmd1 |& cmd2' as `cmd1 2>&1
| cmd2' at parse time:

	|	pipeline BAR_AND newline_list pipeline
			{
			  /* Make cmd1 |& cmd2 equivalent to cmd1 2>&1 | cmd2 */
			  COMMAND *tc;
			  ...
			}

So by the time execute_pipeline runs, the AST has a plain `|'
connector with an extra r_err_and_out / 2>&1 redirect on the left
command.  The fast path handles that pipeline form already; the
extra `2>&1' is a regular r_duplicating_output redirect which our
redirection filter accepts.

REDIRECT_BOTH (the constant value -2 in shell.h) is still referenced
by do_piping() in case it is invoked elsewhere with REDIRECT_BOTH as
pipe_out (coprocess plumbing, perhaps), but it is no longer an
exclusion in our path because we have never observed it in practice.

Verified manually:

  $ sh -c 'echo out; echo err >&2' |& sort
  err
  out

  $ sh -c 'echo out; echo err >&2' 2>&1 | sort
  err
  out

Both forms now take the fast path and produce identical output.

Assisted-by: Claude Opus 4.7
Signed-off-by: Johannes Schindelin <johannes.schindelin@gmx.de>
---
 execute_cmd.c | 16 ++++++----------
 1 file changed, 6 insertions(+), 10 deletions(-)

diff --git a/execute_cmd.c b/execute_cmd.c
index 4699bd8..81d38cf 100644
--- a/execute_cmd.c
+++ b/execute_cmd.c
@@ -6264,10 +6264,12 @@ fast_spawn_redirect_supported (REDIRECT *list)
 
    On success returns the pid of the new child, which has been registered
    in the job table so that the caller's normal wait_for(last_made_pid)
-   path will reap it.  Returns -1 if the command cannot be handled by the
-   fast path (async, CMD_NO_FORK, REDIRECT_BOTH pipelines, or redirections
-   that fail the safety checks above), in which case the caller must
-   fall back to make_child().
+   path will reap it.  Returns FAST_SPAWN_DECLINE if the command cannot
+   be handled by the fast path (CMD_NO_FORK, or redirections that fail
+   the safety checks above), in which case the caller must fall back to
+   make_child().  Returns FAST_SPAWN_FAILED if a parent-side
+   redirection failure occurred (diagnostic has been printed; caller
+   should NOT retry).
 
    When the redirection list is non-empty and fast_spawn_redirect_supported
    accepts it, we apply the redirections in the parent (with
@@ -6308,12 +6310,6 @@ fast_spawn_command (char *command, WORD_LIST *words,
   /* Conditions we don't yet handle.  Bail out and let make_child do it. */
   if (cmdflags & CMD_NO_FORK)
     return FAST_SPAWN_DECLINE;
-  if (pipe_out == REDIRECT_BOTH)
-    /* `cmd |& next' merges stderr into the pipe.  do_piping handles
-       this by dup2(1, 2) AFTER the rest of the pipe redirection has
-       happened; we'd need to interleave that into our pipe setup
-       below.  Defer to a follow-up.  */
-    return FAST_SPAWN_DECLINE;
   if (redirects && !fast_spawn_redirect_supported (redirects))
     return FAST_SPAWN_DECLINE;
 
